<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-04T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="351" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">612.112/10: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vera Cruz</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wood</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vera
                                        Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-04T16:00:00-07:00"><hi rend="italic">January 4,
                                        1924—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:28
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>American interests desire Department’s position as to whether they can
                            export and import without being fined and treated as smugglers by the
                            Obregon government in the event of its return here. They refer to
                            article number 6 of Mexican customs regulations <hi rend="italic">Código
                                de Procedimientos Aduaneros Ordenanza General de Aduanas</hi>, pages
                            6 and 7, edition 1912. Respectfully request instructions <pb facs="0533" n="439" xml:id="pg_439"/> by telegraph as large sums are involved
                            covering coffee and sugar shipments awaiting reply.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wood</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>